50|$|In 2012, the CEB lost 61.2 billion rupees and the Ceylon Petroleum Corporation which {{supplied}} fuel below cost 89.7 billion rupees. To {{cover up}} the loss, the CEB increased <b>power</b> <b>tariffs</b> in large scales. The CEB expected to get revenues of 223 billion rupees—or 45 billion rupees more than the earlier tariff—from the price hike, but subsequently lost 33 billion rupees in 2013 on total expenses of 256 billion rupees.|$|R
