30|$|Further policy supports, such as {{establishing}} {{pricing policies}} to encourage grid-friendly wind power projects, could include performance-based incentives or ancillary service cost-sharing. National directives should be strengthened on inter-provincial/inter-regional power exchange. Intra-province wind power transmission cost could be shared through local <b>power</b> <b>tariffs.</b> Inter-provincial and inter-regional UHV transmission costs {{should be covered}} by purchase prices and sale prices in the target province or region. In addition, mutually agreed quota systems and liberalised market mechanisms should be explored and implemented to promote inter-regional power exchange.|$|R
50|$|In 2011-2012, {{when the}} state of Tamil Nadu {{was in the midst}} of a severe power crisis leading to exorbitant <b>power</b> <b>tariffs</b> and failure of {{industries}} in the state, the management of Neyveli Lignite Corporation, a central government held entity in Neyveli, Tamil Nadu was contemplating divesting shares to private players. This immediately sparked public unrest in the state, and most of its employees organizing a massive strike against the central government's decision. The corporation is accused of then allegedly manipulating its workers and indulging in acts to swiftly play down the issue.|$|R
40|$|Tendencies and {{perspectives}} {{for development of}} thermal and electric <b>power</b> <b>tariffs</b> for population and industry in Belarus have been analyzed in the paper. The average Belarusian tariffs are compared with the corresponding ones in other countries. It is revealed that the current tariff distribution for population and industry in the Republic does not stimulate the economical usage of electric power and deteriorates an export potential of the Belarusian enterprises. It is determined that due to an increase of fuel-power resource prices {{it will be necessary}} also to increase further prices of generated power resources and, first of all, prices of electrical power of non-industrial consumer groups.  </p...|$|R
